{{Infobox university | name = Biblical Theological Seminary | image = Biblical Theological Seminary logo.jpg | former_name = Biblical School of Theology | motto = ''Following Jesus into the world. | established = 1971 | type = [[Private school|Private]], [[Non-profit organization|Nonprofit]], [[Christian school|Christian]] | endowment = | staff = | faculty = | president = [[Frank A. James, III]] | chancellor = | students = 300 | undergrad = | postgrad = | doctoral = | profess = | city = [[Hatfield, Pennsylvania|Hatfield]] | state = [[Pennsylvania]] | country = [[United States]] | campus = Hatfield, Pennsylvania & [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] | free_label = | free = | colors = Blue and Gold | nickname = | affiliations = [[Middle States Commission on Higher Education]] [[Association of Theological Schools in the United States and Canada]] | footnotes = | website = [http://www.biblical.edu www.biblical.edu] | coor = | logo = }}
'''Biblical Theological Seminary''' is an [[interdenominational]] [[graduate school]] of [[theology]] known for its [[missional]] emphasis. Biblical is currently located in [[Hatfield, Pennsylvania]] (a suburb of Philadelphia) at the former Hatfield High School campus. In May 2018 it announced that it will change its name to '''Missio Seminary''' (effective October 2018) and relocate to a new facility in the [[Logan Square, Philadelphia|Logan Square]] neighborhood of Philadelphia (in January 2019).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/BiblicalSeminary/videos/772460476276053/|title=A New Place and a New Name|last=|first=|date=May 16, 2018|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>
==History==
Biblical Seminary was founded in 1971 as the Biblical School of Theology by [[Jack W. Murray]], president of [[Bible Evangelism, Inc.]] and founder of the now-closed [[Clearwater Christian College]], and [[Allan MacRae|Allan A. MacRae]], a former president of [[Faith Theological Seminary]], who served as the seminary's first president.<ref>"History," [http://www.biblical.edu/pages/discover/history.htm www.bibical.edu], {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070328195358/http://www.biblical.edu/pages/discover/history.htm|date=March 28, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.biblical.edu/about-bts/about-bts/our-heritage|title=Honoring Our Heritage {{!}} Biblical Seminary|website=www.biblical.edu|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> The former E.B. Laudenslager public school in Hatfield, Pennsylvania was renovated to house the new school. In 1978 the name was changed to Biblical Theological Seminary.
[[Frank A. James, III]] was inaugurated as Biblical's fourth president in 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thereporteronline.com/article/RO/20130630/NEWS01/130639962|title=Biblical Seminary in Hatfield Borough transitioning to new president|access-date=2018-05-16|language=en}}</ref> James previously served as provost of [[Gordon-Conwell Theological Seminary]] and president of [[Reformed Theological Seminary]].
==Academics== The seminary received regional [[school accreditation|accreditation]] from the [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Schools]] in 1990<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.msche.org/institutions_view.asp?idinstitution=37|title=Middle States Commission on Higher Education|last=Ltd.|first=Info724|website=www.msche.org|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> and from the [[Association of Theological Schools in the United States and Canada]] in 1996.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ats.edu/member-schools/biblical-theological-seminary|title=Biblical Theological Seminary {{!}} The Association of Theological Schools|website=www.ats.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref>
The seminary offers the [[Master of Arts]] (M.A.), [[Master of Divinity]] (M.Div.), [[Master of theology|Master of Theology]] (Th.M) and [[Doctor of Ministry]] (D.Min.) degrees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.biblical.edu/academic-programs-degree-landing|title=All Programs Available at Biblical Seminary|website=www.biblical.edu|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-05-16}}</ref> Certificate programs are also offered, as well as online courses.
In addition to the school's regular full-time and part-time faculty, various prominent scholars have served as visiting professors or adjunct faculty, including [[Scot McKnight]], [[D. A. Carson]], [[Tim Keller (pastor)|Timothy Keller]] and [[Peter Enns]].
