{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Billy Bassett | image = | fullname = William Edward George Bassett<ref>{{Hugman|1117|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref> | birth_date = {{Birth date|1912|06|8|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Brithdir, Caerphilly]], Wales | death_date = {{death year and age|1977|1912}} | death_place = [[Pwllheli]], [[Caernarvonshire]], Wales<ref>''England & Wales, Civil Registration Death Index, 1916-2007''</ref> | height = | position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]] | youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = | years1 = ?–1933 | years2 = 1933–1934 | years3 = 1934–1938 | years4 = 1938–1949 | years5 = 1949–? | clubs1 = [[Aberaman Athletic F.C.|Aberaman Athletic]] | clubs2 = [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] | clubs3 = [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] | clubs4 = [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] | clubs5 =[[Porthmadog F.C.|Porthmadog]] | caps1 = | caps2 = 0 | caps3 = 154 | caps4 = 70 | caps5 = | goals1 = | goals2 = 0 | goals3 = 2 | goals4 = 0 | goals5 = | nationalyears1 = | nationalteam1 = | nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 = }} '''William Edward George Bassett''' (8 June 1912 – 1977) was a Welsh professional [[Association football|footballer]]. During his career, he made over 200 appearances in the [[Football League]] in spells with [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] and [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].
==Career== Bassett began his career at [[Aberaman Athletic F.C.|Aberaman Athletic]] before moving on to [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] in 1933. He only spent a single season at Wolves, without making a first team appearance, before returning to Wales and signing for manager [[Ben Watts-Jones]] at [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]]. He made his debut on the opening day of the 1934–35 season during a 2–1 victory over [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] and was a virtual ever present in his four years, scoring two goals for the Bluebirds, against [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] and [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]].
He joined [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] in 1938 but the outbreak of [[World War II]] interrupted his spell at the [[London]] side and he served in the [[Welsh Guards]] during the hostilities. He finished his league career after three years with the club and took over as player-manager of [[Porthmadog F.C.|Porthmadog]].<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Who's Who of Cardiff City | first = Dean | last = Hayes | publisher = Breedon Books | year = 2006 | p=19 | location=Derby | isbn= 1-85983-462-0}}</ref>
